narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: how to write papers in continental philosophy (more rhetorical, and definitely more fun to write!), and so much about existentialist philosophy and the life of Simone de Beauvoir
I learned a ton about the work of Simone de Beauvoir and how her philosophical thinking evolved over the course of her life.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
strengths- amazing professor, readings were really well structured
not really a weakness but i would have loved to watch a documentary about her or read some of her memoirs, to learn more about her personal life.

There was way too much reading - it was challenging to manage and we rarely discussed most of it. The class would be better if shorter, more specific excerpts were selected for discussion. The content was fascinating and Manon is brilliant. However, I don't think that a seminar format was the best possible format for this class. Since all of us were relatively unfamiliar with Beauvoir's work and with continental philosophy more broadly, it was rare that we contributed something particularly valuable to class discussions. I think it would be better as a lecture - Manon is incredibly engaging and knows so much about Beauvoir. We also got very little feedback on our work.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes if you have taken a philosophy course before and you are interested in continental philosophy.
